  "text": "## Health Check Endpoint Implementation Comparison Across Go Projects\n\n### Kubernetes (kubernetes/kubernetes)\n\n**Endpoints:** `/healthz`, `/livez`, `/readyz`\n\nKubernetes uses a comprehensive health checking framework located in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz/healthz.go`. The main implementation functions are:\n\n- **InstallHandler()**: Registers handlers for `/healthz` endpoint (line 171)\n- **InstallReadyzHandler()**: Registers handlers for `/readyz` endpoint (line 179)\n- **InstallLivezHandler()**: Registers handlers for `/livez` endpoint (line 187)\n- **InstallPathHandlerWithHealthyFunc()**: Core function that registers health checkers with optional callback (line 202)\n\nKubernetes implements multiple built-in health checkers:\n\n1. **PingHealthz**: Simple check that always returns OK (lines 52-64)\n2. **LogHealthz**: Verifies logging is not blocked by checking if klog.Flush() completes within 2 minutes (lines 67-92)\n3. **InformerSyncHealthz**: Checks if all informers in the cache are synced (lines 98-152)\n4. **ShutdownHealthz**: Fails when the process receives shutdown signal (lines 115-136)\n5. **Custom HealthCheckers**: Components add domain-specific checks (e.g., informer sync in controller-manager)\n\n**Component-Specific Implementations:**\n\n- **kube-scheduler** (`cmd/kube-scheduler/app/server.go`, lines 374-376): Registers readiness checks including `NewShutdownHealthz()`, `sched-handler-sync` (custom check), and informer sync. The `newEndpointsHandler()` function calls `InstallHandler()`, `InstallLivezHandler()`, and `InstallReadyzHandler()`.\n\n- **kube-proxy** (`cmd/kube-proxy/app/server.go`, line 465): Calls `healthz.InstallHandler()` with no arguments, defaulting to PingHealthz\n\n- **kubelet** (`pkg/kubelet/server/server.go`, lines 427-433): Installs handlers with three checks: `PingHealthz`, `LogHealthz`, and a custom `syncloop` check via `host.SyncLoopHealthCheck`\n\n- **kube-proxy health check** (`pkg/proxy/healthcheck/proxy_health.go`): Custom implementation with `ProxyHealthServer` that returns JSON status. Implements separate `healthzHandler` (line 219) and `livezHandler` (line 251) that check proxier synchronization status and node eligibility. Returns HTTP 503 if unhealthy, 200 if healthy.\n\n### Grafana (grafana/grafana)\n\n**Endpoints:** `/healthz`, `/livez`, `/readyz`\n\nGrafana implements health endpoints in two main locations:\n\n1. **pkg/server/health.go**: Defines the health check framework with:\n   - **HealthNotifier** struct (lines 12-34): Thread-safe mechanism using atomic.Bool to signal readiness\n   - **LivezHandler()** (lines 36-43): Always returns 200 OK to indicate process is alive\n   - **ReadyzHandler()** (lines 45-57): Returns 200 OK if `HealthNotifier.IsReady()` is true, otherwise 503 Service Unavailable\n   - **RegisterHealthEndpoints()** (lines 61-64): Registers both endpoints on router with GET methods\n\n2. **pkg/api/http_server.go**: Implements basic `/healthz` health check\n   - **healthzHandler** (around line 756): Middleware handler that returns 200 OK if request method is GET/HEAD and path is `/healthz`\n\nGrafana uses a simpler model than Kubernetes, with initialization status tracked by a `HealthNotifier` that components call `SetReady()` on when they complete initialization. The `/livez` endpoint always responds with 200 OK, while `/readyz` depends on the initialization status.\n\n### Prometheus (prometheus/prometheus)\n\n**Endpoints:** `/-/healthy`, `/-/ready` (note: different naming convention with `/-/` prefix instead of `/`)\n\nPrometheus implements health checks in `web/web.go` with:\n\n1. **/-/healthy endpoint** (lines 591-597): Simple liveness check\n   - GET handler returns 200 with message \"%s is Healthy.\"\n   - HEAD handler returns 200 OK\n   - Always returns healthy status (simple ping check)\n\n2. **/-/ready endpoint** (lines 598-604): Readiness check with state management\n   - Wraps handler with `readyf()` function (alias for `h.testReady`)\n   - GET handler returns 200 with message \"%s is Ready.\" only when ready\n   - HEAD handler returns 200 OK only when ready\n\n**Key Implementation Details** (lines 641-677):\n\n- **SetReady()** (lines 642-651): Sets ready status using atomic operation (Handler.ready)\n  - When status is `Ready`: stores uint32(Ready) and sets metrics.readyStatus to 1\n  - Otherwise: stores status value and sets metrics.readyStatus to 0\n\n- **isReady()** (lines 654-656): Atomic read of ready status\n\n- **testReady()** (lines 659-677): Wrapper function that:\n  - Calls handler function f if status is `Ready`\n  - Returns 503 Service Unavailable if status is `NotReady` or `Stopping`\n  - Sets `X-Prometheus-Stopping` header to true if stopping, false if not ready\n\nPrometheus manages three ready states: `Ready`, `NotReady`, and `Stopping`, allowing graceful shutdown detection. The `/-/ready` endpoint supports both GET and HEAD methods and checks the state before executing the handler.\n\n## Key Differences Summary\n\n| Feature | Kubernetes | Grafana | Prometheus |\n|---------|------------|---------|------------|\n| Endpoint Paths | /healthz, /livez, /readyz | /healthz, /livez, /readyz | /-/healthy, /-/ready |\n| Main Check File | staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/healthz/ | pkg/server/health.go | web/web.go |\n| Check Types | Plugin-based (HealthChecker interface) | Simple initialization flag | State-based (Ready/NotReady/Stopping) |\n| DB Checks | Custom implementations per component | Not explicitly shown | Not explicitly shown |\n| Dependencies | Informer sync, leader election, component handlers | Application initialization status | Configuration readiness |\n| Detail Level | Supports verbose mode with per-check status | Simple OK/not-ready response | JSON state with metrics |\n"
}

